- 1 teaspoon salt

- 2 egg yolks
- 4 tablespoons olive oil
Chicken and Caramelized Onion Sauce:
- 3 tablespoons olive oil
- 1 red onion, chopped
- 2 teaspoons minced fresh sage
- 1 teaspoon minced fresh thyme
- 2 large cloves garlic, finely sliced
- 2 large chicken breasts, cut into 3/4 inch cubes
- 2 cups heavy cream
- 1 cup chicken stock
- 3 teaspoons brown sugar
- oil for ravioli maker
Prepare the ravioli dough first, combining the flour, cocoa powder, and salt in a large bowl. Using a mixer with a dough hook, beat the large eggs, egg yolks, and olive oil together, and gradually incorporate the dry mixture. Once the dough is formed and set aside, it is time to prepare the filling. Remove the seeds and marrow from the pumpkin and peel off the tough skin, reserving squash pulp, seeds, and marrow.
Melt 2 tablespoons of butter in a large pan over medium high heat. Instantly add pumpkin seeds to a single layer, roasting until sizzling loudly, stirring constantly, until the seeds begin to pop, about 1 minute. <s> Ford is building cars that "talk" with traffic lights, road signs and pedestrians.
At CES 2019 in Las Vegas on Monday, the automaker announced plans to start selling cars that feature this type of technology, known as autonomous vehicle-to-infrastructure (AV-to-infra) communications. The technology will be first offered on Ford's , a mid-size sedan set to premiere at the North American International Auto Show this month. Ford said it committed $4 billion over the next five years to developing new mobility solutions for cities, indicating that this timeframe could be when the cars hit the market.
AV-to-infrastructure communications, also sometimes called vehicle-to-infrastructure, is a term used to describe cars communicating within their surroundings. Technology like this is considered important for autonomous vehicles, which will need to know what's in the environment around them even if no one is actually driving. For example, some cars use GPS or dedicated short-range communications to connect with traffic lights, road signs and other infrastructure.
The technology Ford introduced could be especially useful. It gathers information from traffic lights and sends corresponding braking instructions to stop lights in the car's front end, regardless of whether the signal is red or green. For example, if a red light goes green but the car isn't stopped, the technology could signal the vehicles to stop at the last instant. Ford's new cars will also be able to change lanes automatically based on this technology.
Ford added that its cars will be able to "talk" with pedestrians using signs, gestures and signals. Initially this will just make the car more pedestrian-conscious, causing it to slow to a crawl, make panic stops or ... alert the driver to potentially dangerous situations. Later on, the system will "verbally" warn of those dangers. The car will use cameras and loudspeakers to deliver this new feature.
Ford also announced Monday that it is partnering with airport operator to create the new Transit Autonomous Shuttle. By improving on what the OEM calls the "best-selling vehicle in North America", Ford hopes to achieve efficient shuttles. It isn't clear in what cities or airports Instant Transit will operate.

Transport for NSW gave the OK on Wednesday after the State Government announced the transition timeframe for the speed changes.

The change comes after recommendations from the Hunter CBD Clearways Project 2020, which was announced in 2016. The project was developed to encourage new transport services, pedestrian and cycle connections and improved liveability in Newcastle.

The Hunter and Scott streets changes are part of a transport changes package that will help improve the efficiency of CBD roads, reduce congestion and improve the safety of road users.

About 10.9km of corridor will have new set of arrows and speed limits.

The project is aimed at supporting economic growth in the region, improving social outcomes.

“This is a great day,” Mr Crakanthorp said. “Ill start doing some celebrating in a few days [sic]”

The changes are expected to be implemented in stages at the end of May 2018, weather permitting.

Replacement street signs will begin to appear in early April, Transport for NSW road workers will install the final signs in May.

The new speed limits will be effective as soon as the signs are installed.

Following upgrades to Hunter and Scott streets in the CBD, the full package of new CBD residential clearways will be implemented by 2020.

- change the speed limit to 40 km/h on Hunter Street, and Scott Street, between Worth Place and Telford Street,

DEAR READER:
Nearsightedness, called myopia, is an extremely common condition. It affects more than 250 million people around the world. The most common cause of myopia is an eye drawing abnormally long in childhood. When this occurs naturally, it’s called hereditary myopia. Sometimes, this elongation of the eye results from crossing the eyes.
Myopia that develops in adults, though, is almost always due to some other cause: For example, inflammation of the cornea (the clear front surface of the eye), tumors or strabismus (crossed eyes). In any case, a more detailed examination by an eye-care professional should determine what’s causing your son’s vision to rapidly deteriorate.
Refractive surgery or laser vision correction could help your son. Such procedures reshapes the cornea, which can help to correct the refraction of light passing through the eye. That results in improved vision. There are several procedures with different names, but the goal of them all is to try to reshape the elongated cornea toward its normal shape.
I mention these procedures so that you understand that surgery is an option. However, it carries some small risk of complications, and the results may not be perfect. Further, the original cause of the myopia, the elongated eye, usually remains unless there is also surgery to change the shape of the eye. In that case, myopia may return to some degree if the eye’s structure returns to its abnormal shape.

<s> In the market for a low-cost networked storage solution? You may want to take a look at the Netgear ReadyNAS 104.
Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true NAS options. Other than what has been offered from Apple with its AirPort Extreme Base Station, and then later its Time Capsule server, there has traditionally been no other alternative in terms of home-grade NAS.
Now that's likely to change, thanks to Netgear's latest update to its ReadyNAS family of RAID-based networked-attached storage appliances. The latest ReadyNAS Clear, model 104, is the highest-capacity consumer-grade NAS line available to date.
We at FierceContentManagement got our hands on one of these appliances and were quite impressed with what the unit delivers in terms of available ports and ease of use. On the whole, the ReadyNAS 104 unit provides all of the services and functionality you'd need from a network attached storage device.
The guts
When unwrapped from its FedEx packaging, it's easy to see the similarities between the ReadyNAS 104 (available from $300 and up) and ReadyNAS Pro (from $500). The 104 is a much slicker, thinner design. It has changeable, hot-swappable 18" bays, but is tiny in size at 8" square. By comparison, the ReadyNAS Pro has 3.5-inch bays and its front is about the size of a PC tower.
One thing both models do not have is a power button. Instead, they have on/off switches and a red indicator light on the back. The red indicator appears when the device is powered on and hard disks are spinning. Until that red light is illuminated, it's safe to assume the device is not receiving power.
The 104 can hold as many as two 3.5-inch portable hard drives that hold up to 500GB of storage. Both the drives default to FAT32 and can be reformatted to a different file system. When using FAT32, the other systems and devices on the network will recognize the NAS just as if it were a standard storage device like a USB flash drive.

The Frederic Salwe collection comprises nearly 5,000 volumes. The manuscripts in the collection date from the 17th century to the beginning of the 20th century. The collection represents important treasures, parts of which are of exceptional rarities, preserved in volumes and monographs, which reveal much about development trends in world science.

Frederic Salwe began collecting unique Armenian manuscripts from the Armenia diaspora in the first half of the 20th century, with the support of local nun and historian Bactoburtiv Tjan. Following Salwe’s death, his heirs have effectively become curators of the large collection of historical and rarities that Salwe had gathered.

As a social-responsibility initiative, ProCredit Bank launched a project to set up and digitize a special library — the Library of Artsakh — together with the ProCredit Bank Foundation for the Support of Artsakh. In that context, the Bank donated Salwe’s collection of Armenian manuscripts to the Library of Artsakh, making them available to a wide audience and increasing interest in Armenia’s intellectual and spiritual heritage. The Library of Artsakh is a digital collection of books and manuscripts, which was launched by the ProCredit Bank Group. Under development, the database provides a free-access window to the world’s ancient Armenian works. <s> Ubuntu 10.04 LTS Lucid Lynx is the latest Linux operating system from Canonical, aimed at consumers. It's free, but is it sufficiently consumer friendly that you should switch from Windows?

Ubuntu is good for:

- Laptops - Ubuntu works well out of the box with wireless internet connection, and Gmail and Facebook work well in web browsers. It will configure most PC hardware without trouble.

- Mediocre pre-installed hardware - Ubuntu uses less memory (RAM) than Windows, and lots of older, bargain-price laptops are bought with ClearOS or 2GB of memory, sometimes less.

- Business - IT support is easier when personnel can easily change settings to adapt to their own needs, and Ubuntu provides a basic "Apps" interface that simplifies hardware settings.

- User manuals - some laptops have extensive user manuals are easier to access on the desktop, rather than having to be installed with Windows.

## Ubuntu short on business apps

Ubuntu is not ideal for business, however. Much of the software aimed at business is PC-specific, and unlikely to be available, or if it is, won't work with Ubuntu. It's difficult to port large packages from Windows and Microsoft Office, for example. In most businesses, compatibility with change is an issue. The more of your infrastructure has changes, the more opportunities for problems, and at the PC level, moving from one operating system to a completely different one has to be well understood and managed very carefully.

Some companies use low-cost PCs to behave like terminals that do not store files, and work solely with local applications running on the server. If you are running such a setup with Windows apps then the answer is not to try to convert to Ubuntu but to use RDC (Remote Desktop Connection) software such as TightVNC or RealVNC to connect into your existing servers instead.

Users faced with software they are familiar with, such as Microsoft Office, that does not run on Ubuntu, will almost certainly replicate default PC behaviour - deleting or changing files, opening windows, popping icons onto the desktop and installing files. This is not wrong, it's just Windows.

However, while Ubuntu is not going to be suitable for most corporations, I'm less certain it's going to be the answer for home users either.

<s> Advocates for government accountability were alarmed to learn Gov. Jared Polis was undecided on whether to veto a bill to expand police transparency in Colorado.
But Polis spokeswoman Maria De Cambra set the worries to rest Monday, telling Colorado Politics the bill was headed for veto status.

“The governor will be signing the bill vetoing the excessive force provision that contained poorly drafted language that could impose liability on police officers and municipalities for simply doing their jobs in good faith,” De Cambra said in a statement provided to Colorado Politics. “The governor will be signing the bill that, by law, extended the Public Records Law to Clear Creek and Gilpin Counties, and the bill that preserved the language in the citizen’s bill of rights COVID exemption — which had been narrowed in the legislature.”

The bill — House Bill 21-1238 — arrived on the governor’s desk Monday after the House voted Wednesday to reject the changes made in the Senate by a lopsided 25-10.

Two of the tweaks gutted a measure to more effectively combat discriminatory policing by requiring that cases of the excessive use of force against members of minorities be reported to the Peace Officers Standards and Training Board for review.

Polis has tremendous latitude in how he handles a bill that’s on his desk, but a veto would be in keeping with his penchant for doing so.

Since he took office in 2019, Polis has vetoed 69 bills and only two of those still remain in force.

De Cambra said the veto would affect only the excessive force provision in the bill, whereas the others were simply part of technical clean-up legislation.

data.output:
<s> It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions.

### Other Types of Focus

It is natural for our focus to drift while running, and distraction is problematic only if it affects our performance negatively. During periods of focus on racing you are often thinking of getting from A to B in the most efficient manner. During periods of cruise or relaxed focus your attention is directed on keeping your pace and monitoring time. And finally, there are times when we allow the mind to wander wherever it wants, with no particular focus of attention, sometimes this can be quite enjoyable and relaxing, sometimes more difficult.

### Finding Balance

In order to best optimize performance and reach your performance goals, it's important to use varying levels of focus. The most effective runners find the most balance between the above types of focus by experimenting with how much attention to pay to your body, technique, and environment, and also how much attention to pay for the sake of calculated effort.

### Experiment and Practice

For the new runner, regardless of type, practice is key. Mindfulness practices, like meditation, can be helpful in becoming more experienced with helping the mind to pay attention to the present moment. Paying attention for the sake of it is neither a good thing nor a bad thing. It will require experience and experimentation to establish your preference. That said, be careful not to be self critical for what or where your mind goes. Forcing the mind to focus may ultimately make it very difficult for it to do so when it wants to.

Remember, this is about being kind to yourself and enjoying the process. Mindsets are built over time with repeated experiences. The practice of noticing where your mind goes when it isn't paying full attention can be fascinating and quite revealing. From there you can begin to form attention habits that ultimately help your focus in your marathon training. Don't worry too much about what others are thinking, they are probably thinking, "Where did my mind just go?"</s>к</s>к</s>к индиендеи in default.
